1270","omkring 1248":"about 1248","1228":"1228","1248":"1248","1302":"1302","1268":"1268","1289":"1289","1310":"1310","1299":"1299","before 1274":"before 1274","before 1260":"before 1260","after 1253":"after 1253","1309":"1309","1317":"1317","Sweden":"Sweden","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Margareta","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margaret","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]},{"name":"Margarete","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margrethe","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretha","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1357046,"age":96,"year":"1250","julianDay":2177614,"description":"King Eriksson died. Valdemar crowned King. Birger Jarl declared regent until Valdemar is of age.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1702074,"age":98,"year":"1252","julianDay":2178344,"title":"Earliest Mention of Stockholm","description":"The earliest known recorded history of the city of Stockholm is in Norse sagas as Agnafit which dates to 1252. The city rose to prominence due to Baltic trade. Stockholm is now the most populous urban area in the region.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Margareta Petersdotter was born in Sweden as the daughter of Peter Eskilsson Näf and Mrs. Peter Eskilsson. She married Algot Brynolfsson before 1260. They were the parents of at least 8 sons. She died before 1274."},"et":{"–before 1274":"–enne 1274","1268–Male":"1268–Surnud","–1270":"–1270","–1274":"–1274","1228–1302":"1228–1302","1248–1317":"1248–1317","–1289":"–1289","–1299":"–1299","–1309":"–1309","–1310":"–1310","–Male":"Surnud","–1253":"–1253","–Female":"Surnud","1253":"1253","1252":"1252","1274":"1274","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","omkring 1248":"umbes 1248","1228":"1228","1248":"1248","1302":"1302","1268":"1268","1289":"1289"